e reluctance of the North Korean leadership to weaken its grip on foreign economic activity. They argue that inducements have limited effect on the regime, and instead urge policymakers to think in terms of gradual strategies. Hard Target connects economic statecraft to the marketization process to understand North Korea and addresses a larger debate over the merits and demerits of "engagement" with adversaries.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 23. Jul 2020) 0aEconomic sanctionsxKorea (North). 0aEconomic sanctionszKorea (North) 0aEconomic sanctionszKorea (North). 0aNuclear disarmamentxKorea (North). 0aNuclear disarmamentzKorea (North) 0aNuclear disarmamentzKorea (North). 4aNorth Korea. 4aeconomic statecraft. 4aforeign policy. 4anuclear weapons. 4aproliferation. 4asanctions. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Security (National & International).2bisacsh1 aNoland, Marcus, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertSUP Complete eBook-Package 2017z978311070369640uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9781503601994zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781503601994423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781503601994.jpg  a978-3-11-070369-6  SUP Complete eBook-Package 2017b2017  aGBV-deGruyter-alles